    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>The problem is that it just lumps all majors togehter as "college graduates" when all the data shows that in today's market, your area of study -- i.e., your skills --- really matter. &nbsp;I think it would be more relevant to see statistics for specific majors/areas of study to see if there is a "lack of skills" at play here. &nbsp;</p>
<p>I know several people graduating in engineering of various types -- chemical, mechanical. petroleum (big in oil and gas producing states like Louisiana). &nbsp;They are having no trouble finding jobs. &nbsp;I think all the <a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505145_162-57324669/25-college-majors-with-lowest-unemployment-rates/">data</a> shows that your major -- your "skills" have a LOT to do with your <a href="http://news.yahoo.com/blogs/lookout/10-college-majors-lowest-unemployment-rates-163049193.html">chances of getting a job</a>. &nbsp;If you Google some form of "least employable degrees," you will find that <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/jennagoudreau/2012/10/11/the-10-worst-college-majors/">same areas</a> over and over -- various forms of arts and humanities, along with psychology, typically lead <a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505145_162-57325132/25-college-majors-with-the-highest-unemployment-rates/">the lists</a>. &nbsp; Simpy put, if you major in something like dance, or art history, or film, your chances of finding a job that uses your degree are much, much lower than if you major in Electrical Engineering. &nbsp;</p>
<p>If it is true that some areas of study have very low unemployment rates and some have very high unemployment rates, then there may be a mismatch of skills to demand. &nbsp;I don't think it paints an accurate picture, in today's job market, to lump all college graduates together. &nbsp;More and more, the area of study <a href="http://graphicsweb.wsj.com/documents/NILF1111/#term=">really matters</a>. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:120104">coffeetalk</a> on <a href="/comments/1211849/50280015#c8">Mon May 27, 2013 at 03:34:10 PM PDT</a></p>
