<p>we need to be realistic with college students. &nbsp;If you are going to borrow $150,000 to go to college and major in art history, financially it might be smarter to consider forgoing college and learning a marketable trade or skill. &nbsp;Or maybe, if you are set on college, consider a major in a high demand area, or even a moderately high demand area, and a minor in the area you love.</p>
<p>I'm not sure how you would think the private sector will create more jobs for those "high rate of unemployment" majors. &nbsp;The job market, like any other market, responds to demand, and if there's a very low demand for Library Science majors -- as there apparently is -- people who chose that major need to be realistic about their employment opportunities in that field. &nbsp;The job market just doesn't "create" jobs because people like that field. &nbsp;You can't graduate in film, or anthropology, or library science, and think that someone owes you a job. Life doesn't work that way. &nbsp;Most things in life are a trade-off. &nbsp;If you major in something you love but that is not in demand, the trade off is that you will have a harder time finding a job that uses that major and usually you can expect to make less money if you do. &nbsp;</p>

