  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Our American economy hasn't been able to achieve full employment without financial bubbles since the early 1970's. &nbsp;The private sector has finally reached it maximum capacity to expand spending (RE:GDP) though increasing its debt load. &nbsp;Private sector debt topped off at over 300% debt to GDP at the height of the bubble in 2008 before starting to come down...thats over $40 trillion! &nbsp;Now that the private sector is re-balancing its books or deleveraging.... we should expect to see continued depressed demand until such a time when private sector debt has bottomed out and starts to climb again absent any new fiscal expansion by the Federal Govt. &nbsp;At the current pace of deleveraging, it looks like we still have almost a decade left assuming we don't have any new recessions to make the problem even worse. &nbsp;If incomes were higher and growing than we might be able to expect to see some economic and demand growth coming out of increased wages but with our real unemployment rate (U-6) still around ~15%, that doesn't look likely.</p>
<p>Everyone should definitely check out this post for a much more detailed summary of the ways in which our economy has been damaged in the last 4 decades by faulty neo-liberal economic mythology, and with lots of great graphs to illustrate our economic reality.</p>
