    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>nuanced (see my comment above about why the area of study matters greatly). &nbsp;</p>
<p>I looked it up, but as I suspected, the percent of adults with a college degree has hit a <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/24/education/census-finds-bachelors-degrees-at-record-level.html?_r=0">record high</a>. &nbsp;</p>
<p>I suspect that a generation ago, someone with a college degree -- any degree, in any area -- was generally more valuable in the job market simply because fewer job applicants had college degrees. &nbsp;</p>
<p>When you have far more people (as a percent of the population) that have college degrees, the degree <em>in and of itself</em> is not as valuable in the job market, simply because it's not as rare. &nbsp;In today's market, when almost a third of adults have college degrees, the area of study matters much more, I suspect.</p>
<p>In other words, it may well be that there is still a "skills gap." &nbsp;The "skills gap" simply is not that there are not enough college graduates; it may be that there are not enough graduates in areas of demand. &nbsp;While there are more people with degrees, the question is whether is whether those degrees are in the areas of demand, or come with the skills that today's market is demanding. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
