<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:117205">Cat Servant</a>, <a href="/user/uid:642">bink</a>, <a href="/user/uid:231987">Eric Nelson</a>, <a href="/user/uid:76994">ebohlman</a>, <a href="/user/uid:167631">Egalitare</a>, <a href="/user/uid:332663">helpImdrowning</a>, <a href="/user/uid:324618">Papuska</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>economy and those once were cured by companies training their employees or trade union/corporate apprenticeship programs. The issue is demand and declining wages, not skills mismatches. Shifting the burden of training and acquisition of job skills from the hiring company to the individual worker. Placing the economic burden on the individual and not the corporation.</p>
<p>The excuse of skills mismatches is just another red herring for the neoliberal Democrats and Republicans that want to create a highly skilled but completely indebted workforce. Taking advantage of job insecurity to lower wages and benefits is an old game. &nbsp;Demanding that employees acquire skills at their own expense that are job specific to the needs of corporations and then hiring that person for as little pay as possible, is the new manifestation of that old game.</p>
<p>Creating a highly indebted, low payed work force with little job mobility and fewer benefits is the dream world of the employer and the nightmare of the employed and those seeking work.</p>
<p>This whole argument is about power, the power of corporations to dictate the policies that affect workers and economic activity generally. The workforce skills mismatch is simply a crypto-fascist argument to make social responsibility seem passe. To shift all social goods into the hands of private interests and to make moral judgements of worker value instead of social judgements about systemic failure. If the problem is a lazy unskilled workforce, then corporations and government have no place in providing a solution, which is exactly the position of the neoliberals. This whole skills mismatch position is simply a piece of neoliberal propaganda, not an honest economic argument. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
"Intelligence is quickness in seeing things as they are..." George Santayana
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:119114">KJG52</a> on <a href="/comments/1211849/50280584#c33">Mon May 27, 2013 at 05:27:17 PM PDT</a></p>
