<li id="c34">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50280609">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Maybe the elephant in the room is </span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1211849/50280609#c34?mode=alone;showrate=1#c34">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:12548">Caj</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>the fact that many colleges turn out people that are not getting what they paid for.</p>
<p>College course that are, on paper, qualifying people to work, actually aren't giving students the skills they are purported to have. &nbsp; In many cases, it's a poorly run resort, a holding tank for kids that will put up with them and keep them from hurting themselves until they mature to a point where they aren't as dangerous to society.</p>
<p>Really bright students that take a lot of AP courses and study on their own do well, graduate, and get good jobs.</p>
<p>Other students, who don't know the material beforehand, expect to be 'taught' the information and skills they don't have, and demoralized grad students and TA's aren't that helpful while the course teacher is off somewhere.</p>
<p>Kids with the advanced social skills already taught them by their parents over family dinner and at family social events are successful competing for the attention of the college. &nbsp;</p>
<p>Those from lesser backgrounds who aren't attractive, poised and pushy pay their money, but don't get a return. &nbsp;They see that college really is no a ladder up, but they don't dare tell their parents how poor their experience is because they don't want to seem ungrateful and wrong. &nbsp;</p>
<p>Cost of college has gone with the increase in loan money available, not any increase in quality.</p>
<p>Likewise, it floors me that so many premed students who do well, take up space in those classes, and then end up running the family business, like a restaurant or dry cleaners that their parents struggled with in order to pay their tuition. &nbsp;</p>
<p>College ain't what is seems. &nbsp; It's as much a con game as shells and peanuts.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:75477">fastwacks</a> on <a href="/comments/1211849/50280609#c34">Mon May 27, 2013 at 05:31:38 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


