<li id="c50">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50281214">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">The study seems to address pretty traditional </span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1211849/50281214#c50?mode=alone;showrate=1#c50">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>career tracts. Get a degree, get a job that at least gets your foot in the door of your chosen career.</p>
<p>Education is becoming hybridized - some classes, some life experiences, internships, certificates -- resumes are more patchwork than they used to be (I should have links to the information behind this thought, I know - hoping to write a diary on some of the current trends - no time to go searching at the moment).</p>
<p>What about entrepreneurships that can get started while still with your family our at a relatively young (like college) age? What about the trades? What about free-lancing?</p>
<p>A college degree is a really expensive investment that not all career or life paths require. It takes creativity to get by and to find your way.</p>
<p>And creative careers like design, art, theater, writing, certainly don't require degrees, but I have a friend who pushed her artistic son through four expensive years of college that he hated (her debt, fortunately for him). He is fine living in someone's garage and painting - taking paid jobs for murals when he could get them. I don't think he's worried about more than getting by.</p>
<p>I'm encouraging my kids to look at a wide range of options, unlike my parents who never offered up any advice beyond getting a college degree. Not very useful in the end.</p>
<p>I'm loving learning about all the options and possible paths with my kids. I'm discovering new paths for myself.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:644715">Elizaveta</a> on <a href="/comments/1211849/50281214#c50">Mon May 27, 2013 at 07:13:39 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	





<li id="c74">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50282758">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">some college degrees more useful than others</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1211849/50282758#c74?mode=alone;showrate=1#c74">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Where I teach, I see a lot of kids majoring in psychology, French literature, and other "soft" liberal arts fields that are not especially useful in the job market. The school is trying to encourage them to pair those up with minors in business, graphic design, or something else that's more job-related. (For example, one of my French major kids is minoring in International Business -- smart move.) I'm torn; as a humanities person I want to see well-educated people in terms of culture and literature and history and all that. I don't want to see colleges become just trade schools. But keeping an eye on "what might you do with this out there in the world?" seems prudent too.</p>
<p>When you add in the kids who aren't doing much real work in college, just sliding through and enjoying "the college experience," I'm not surprised that employers don't necessarily give them much extra credit for that. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:115429">rugbymom</a> on <a href="/comments/1211849/50282758#c74">Tue May 28, 2013 at 05:33:01 AM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	





